commentBody:
@Lauri 

We hope that you'll join us in reliving and arguing about the puzzle with us.  Especially the "arguing".  We argue incessantly, but only over matters of utterly trivial importance.

I don't think we have a regular from the Emerald Isle, do we?  We've got England and Scotland, but I don't think we have Ireland.  (Forgive me if I'm forgetting someone.)

@Francis 

I think there was a woman from County Sligo — Catherine, maybe — who was a regular here for a while. But it’s been some time since I have seen a comment from her. 

I expect there are others in Ireland who regularly contribute here, but like you, I can’t think of any names.

@Mike 
Who hews hues? 
A promising premise presumes a prism.

@Mike 
I just knew Mike would show up with one of his off-color jokes.

I'm seeing red!

@Puzzlemucker 

Missed your wisdom last few days, Mucker! Thanks for the Douglass speech.

Although I'm thinking IRONS are what we need, and the sooner the better!

@john ezra 

The entire speech (14 pages ) is masterful.  Worth reading and I would not have but for this puzzle.  So thanks to the editors for the clue.  Note that when I searched the neh.gov site, I could not find the speech, which possibly was due to my own faulty searching or possibly it was scrubbed.  

In solidarity, my friend.  May we survive these days and come through on the other side.  Always look forward to reading your stuff!

@Puzzlemucker 

Bravo.  And very apropos.

The more things change, the more they stay the same.

@Cat Lady Margaret 

YELLOW + one more I slipped in for fun

So, I ended up at this club called the ROYALE which was recommended by my niece and her friends.  Sorry, but ICANTEVEN. The kids these days, they don't dance, just GYRATE. And the music, if that's what you call it, GRATEs on my nerves! Not to mention the smell of REEFer or POT or whatever the word is nowadays wafting through the club. Felt like a PLOT to destroy my last nerve. I need a REFerral to a good PSYchotherapist. The last one I saw didn't really talk but would just APE my facial expressions and insist on using the ROYALWE.  Maybe instead of a head shrink, I just need to close my eyes and return to my happy place in the ALPEs in Springtime, a picnic basket in my hand and a POSY in my hair. Ahhhhhh...

@john ezra 

EMO Phillips was one of the few standup comics I really enjoyed. Picture a male Olive Oyl. 

It’s been years since I have seen any of his routines, so I won’t do him the disservice of trying to recreate one of them. I particularly liked one about being stopped for speeding (hi, sotto voce!)

@Michael 

I don’t really consider this a rebus, either. In fact, I thought the rebus haters might enjoy this one because they got to drop a letter rather than squeezing two into the box! 

Silly me.

@Patti 

In other words, you weren’t able to solve the puzzle and somehow that is the fault of the constructor? OK, then.

(Putting some letters INSIDE THE LINE is not some arbitrary assumption. It is the literal theme of the puzzle.)

@Patti
It’s plural because there are multiple coloured lines

The latter interpretation is correct because the omitted letters are included within that coloured line, as the revealer reveals. The other interpretation doesn’t work because of the downs.

@sotto voce 

In my household, you ate what was on your plate (including the frozen spinach you’d allowed to get cold in the hope you might be excused from the table without eating it).

I got special treatment only when dinner involved tomato sauce, which I hated as a kid. (What kid won’t eat pizza? Me.) When my mom was browning the ground beef for the spaghetti or whatever, she would fry a hamburger patty for me.

@Min 

Love this!  Great story and apt analogy.

Like the infamous Natick, perhaps we should dub some puzzles "have the salad" moments...

@Eric Hougland 

Whoa, you got special treatment? Congratulations! That's a huge achievement.

My middle brother's technique for dodging having to eat what he didn't like– and one i adopted – was to shove food off the plate, all around it and under its rim, onto the table. My mother only saw it when the table was cleared, and just assumed we were really messy eaters. 😂

@B Don’t get me wrong, I wish more Sydneysiders said stuff like g’day mate. I moved here from Brisbane years ago and I miss the laid back friendliness of Brisbane sometimes. Although there are many great things about Sydney. I just find the idea of saying gday mate in a broad country accent to strangers around here quite funny.  Although to be fair I still say gday a lot. 

Maybe my example in NY wasn’t the best chosen. Merely trying to point out that stereotypical national idioms can sound amusingly out of place in big cities anywhere in the world.  Which was kind of the whole joke with the movie crocodile Dundee.

And I’m not being sarcastic when I say that people would love a usa tourist pulling out a cheesy gday mate in an inner city cafe.

@RP 

Eavesdropping on a conversation like this, from people completely across the globe....it may be almost worth the price of the subscription all by itself.

A really stupid question:  why wouldn't "g'day mate" in Sydney be wise?  I'm assuming there are culture differences across Australia just like anywhere else, but I have absolutely no idea what they are.

@Nora 

I checked and toggled Show Overlays on and off. Colors! No colors!

It might’ve been helpful if there had been a note telling online solvers to turn overlays on.

@Joey 

I love your suspicious nature, to check it even on a Saturday.  Good for you.  That's how you avoid getting caught off guard.

I think I struggled more to "get it", but I absolutely agree that to me, violet = indigo = purple.  And I couldn't see (in fact I'd bet it rarely clearly seen) the difference between the indigo and the violet.  In fact it's sometimes ROYGBV, leaving indigo out altogether.

@Francis 

I was personally surprised to learn from the comments some people expected a rebus. I got the revealer late so it was irrelevant for my solve but the letters in the names of the colors were right there, were they not? 

I guess that's what can happen with a tricky puzzle - some slightly dim people like me will get it for some random reason, while some more inteligent people will miss it for another.

@BlueDropRedSea 

How did you not notice the colored lines? Do you have Show Overlays turned off?  That’s never a good idea; I don’t know why they even allow that option. 

And if you put two letters in each square, how did you justify the resulting down answers?

@MB 
Rainbow order:
Richard Of York Gave Battle In Vain.

@Heidi 
I, too, thought this puzzle was a tour-de-force! When reading these comments, I found myself becoming increasingly cranky at the number of whiners. This puzzle, after all, had a revealer which literally explained the trick! There are times, certainly, when I may not be especially quick-on-the-uptake, due to attempting a solve when I’m overly tired or otherwise stressed, but I try to simply slap my forehead and acknowledge a “D’oh!” moment (or moments!). 

The strategy you delineated in your comment is one I also employ. I hope some of those who were genuinely struggling will read your suggestions and find them helpful in the future. Of course, not everyone will enjoy every puzzle equally, but it seems sad to me that so many are so quick to dismiss a clever, artfully constructed puzzle because they are unwilling to think outside the box.

@Andrzej 

The NOSHADE is just an American idiom.  I think somewhere along the line somebody expressed that criticizing a person was "throwing shade", as if blocking light was a bad thing.  

I think we used to have a much better one when I was about 14 or 15.  It was "No heat".  Like if things were getting a little confrontational you could try to back things down a bit by saying "No heat".  Or you could say it metaphorically, like "I mean no disrespect...", or the clue "No offense..."

@Francis

Thank you. I'll try to remember the expression now that I understand it 👍🏾

@RM 

Thanks! I thought it would be something like that. Over here forms are also numbered, and we do in fact refer to them in speech by those numbers, occasionally, mostly in a tax context, too.

@RM 
Thank you, I've just about learnt SSN. 
There used to be a form UB40 (Unemployment Benefit Form 40) which was used to claim benefits, and a band used it for their name. Unemployment was incredibly high in UK in 1980's.

@Rahul 

I feel you. I liked the puzzle but possibly because I always Google the proper nouns, abbreviations, etc. The effect for the solve is the same as if I knew the answers, and since they are of no interest to me (what do I care about some actor's name or an abbreviation of something random?), I don't even pretend I'm "learning" anything.

Today I got to enjoy the innovative theme without the frustration of dealing with arcana. To me that is a win.

@Francis 

Dang, that was actually quite moving. Thank you. I have a somewhat similar yet less romantic story.

As a teenager I was fascinated by space, too. It was the 90s, when only dial-up internet access was available in Poland. Can you imagine I actually spent some of my extra valuable internet time downloading space telescope images of nebulas? It wasn't all pictures of bare bosoms.

@Francis 

You should check out NASAs APOD.

<a href="https://apod.nasa.gov" target="_blank">https://apod.nasa.gov</a>

@Jenne 

Glad I helped :)

I think Caitlin did not mention it because the option to display overlays is on by default, and only rarely does it happen than individual users have it off - maybe you turned it off by accident once? I know I've done things like that many times in various apps - I fiddle with the options, or I change something by accident, by missclicking, say, and then my user experience is not like that of most people.

@Jacqui J I couldn’t resist sharing the link to Kermit…

<a href="https://youtu.be/WS3Lkc6Gzlk?feature=shared" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/WS3Lkc6Gzlk?feature=shared</a>

Enjoy! 🌈

@Grant 
But those were NOT entries!  PSY, no; POSY, yes.  Both letters were required to complete the entry correctly (according to the clue)...
I knew at once that more letters were needed than spaces allowed, so doubling up was a 'given.'

@quarkcharm ( lilianaklinger) 
Print and pen, Liliana!  Print and pen, and maybe a little colored marker assistance...
If you contact NYT they'll restore your streak, if you wish.

@quarkcharm ( lilianaklinger) 
This has already been said repeatedly, but the clue at 113A literally says the colors are INSIDE the lines. Not to the right. Not to the left. INSIDE.

I am having serious trouble understanding how so many people failed to understand this.

@Corey 
My (late) uncle was color-blind, and while much of the time it did not pose a problem, there were times when it created anxiety and misunderstanding.  

W.S. Et al:  it's not that difficult to look up Accessibility suggestions for assistance.  All of us are always learning, right?

@Mark P & @Andrzej
The tournament is officially called the US Open Tennis Championships, so I suppose "US Open" is an abbreviation:-)
<a href="https://www.usopen.org/index.html" target="_blank">https://www.usopen.org/index.html</a>

@Nancy 

Welcome back! 
You've been so missed!

@Nancy   

Add me to the list of people who missed your comments. Welcome back!

Sorry you had an unpleasant experience here. I hope it was a one-off occurrence.

@Grant 

I don’t remember such a note on the Olympic rings puzzle, but it would have been helpful with this one. 

I honestly don’t know why anyone would want the overlays off — or why the NYT offers that option.

@Mean Old Lady 

On one of our US vacations we were driving from California to Nevada, or maybe it was from Nevada to Utah? Anyway, somewhere on the way we got hungry. Used to European gas stations, which usually stock decent food, we stopped to get a sandwich at a station on the outskirts of a gray, industrial town at the foot of arid mountains. There was nothing fresh, just a row of sad looking, packaged, industrially made sandwiches in a cooler. I reached for one, wary of it - somehow everything in it was strangely pale, and it looked... I don't know... wet? But a distrubing sort of wet, soggy and slimy like something unspeakable Stephen King might write a short story about. So I looked at the ingredients in small print on the label. Ye gods! Turns out the thing that sort of looked like cheese was a "processed non-dairy slice," and the other ingredients were equally scary. I put that abomination back in the cooler, resigning to be hungry rather than violate myself by eating whatever that was.

Gas station food indeed. /shudder

@Brian SF 
Please see the comment directly above yours.

The clue/answer at 113A explains how to solve the puzzle.

@Patti I can see why you thought that. I think that would have eliminated, or at least obscured, another layer of the puzzle, though. Each across answer, as typed, was a real word, just not the word clued. Realizing that helped me with the solve. 

Having to transform a clued word so that it no longer fits the clue, but forms another word, is a frequent trick in these puzzles, I've noticed.

I can't imagine what solving this on a phone would have been like. I found I really needed to see the whole grid to solve this one.

@Patti 

But if you used rebuses in the across answers, the crossing down entries wouldn’t make any sense, right?

I understand why so many people thought to use rebuses (I initially went down that road myself), but I am absolute baffled as to how anyone could fill in the grid with rebus entries and think that it looked correct. What am I missing?

@Paul R 
I had never heard of either, either. However, given the phonotactics--ooh! what a word!--of English, by far the most likely letter was "S." (Although "Eert" sounds like it could be a Dutch name, I guess; and Sebastian Étan, French).

I felt like I should have heard of Sert, tho.

@Barry Ancona 
I have to side with Paul on this one. I know my Marvel movies, and couldn't come up with Sebastian STAN, who played Bucky Barnes, Captain America's sidekick. If you didn't know Cap had a sidekick, it's because he got killed in WWII. Marvel brought him back from the dead for "The Winter Soldier" where he takes over for the real Cap, Steve Rogers. Mr. STAN is currently playing a young Donald Trump in a movie of which I was not aware. I couldn't tell you anything about Mr. SERT, as the only time I'd been to Rockefeller Canter it was for ice skating. I must have seen his name somewhere, though.

Verdict: Natick

@Barry Ancona 

It seems obvious to me.

Ask some friends.

@Helen Wright 

They get taken down, for some reason.  We dare not ask the emus for an explanation, lest we incur their wrath.

Usually with mine it's because I've replied to a post that was taken down.

@Byron 
Mine was AENE_I_D / LAND_I_S (had an A there).
Any help?

@Matt 

What premise?  What misleading?  Who said it was a rebus?  You did apparently.  You mislead yourself and now you're mad at us?

My God, the forum is just filled with the highly entitled.  "I'm entitled to solve this puzzle, so anything that prevented me from solving it must be 'misleading'".

@Dan 

Where are you looking for them? They are in their normal place on my laptop and on my phone app. '

Someone else the other day said they were missing though too, so I wonder how you're trying to access or if there is some platform problem?

@dvdmgsr 

“One can argue either way.”

I am absolutely not seeing the argument in favor of rebuses. How would the crossing down entries make *any sense at all* with the rebus approach?

@RIch Garella 

I think @i_w was referring to clarity (or lack thereof) as to specifically what *formats* are accepted technically as correct, NOT to anything concerning the actual puzzling out of the puzzle. I myself was unsure of a few answers being right or not but at the end I sorta decided they were *probably* right and that maybe the problem was the exact format of entry, so I opted to finally delete my rebus-style 'extra letters' from the rainbow-adjacent squares and let those letters/words be covered from "inside the lines". When that didn't get the 'Congrats' page either, I found a recently-spawned typo ("'USePEN'?! How'd that 'e' get in there, it was 'O' a few minutes ago?!") and got it. I didn't mind too much cuz I know sometimes the puzzles are fussy as to EXACTLY how one enters stuff, but I understand i_w's point, and didn't read their comment as some kind of "I don't wanna hafta puzzle out the puzzle type" comment at all.

1,000 points to the constructor for cluing 76A as the wonderful, wonderful EMO Philips instead of using the old standby "genre of music" clue.

@Trish

The letters that make the across answers fit the clues are already represented in the puzzle by the colored lines. Thus, a rebus isn’t needed to add those letters in. It would be redundant. 

While solving, though, I did use rebus boxes to enter the additional letters for the colors. It made it easier to visualize the correct across answers. Then I went back and took the rebuses out.

@Darcey O’D 

God and emus work in mysterious ways.

Sorry you lost your comment.  It's happened to many of us, and without explanation or apology.
